A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they found the solution in a small black box that can be found in the dashboard of every car.
The devices that record every mile travelled and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the federal planning offices to revise the outdated system to finance U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and advocate that the government can use the small boxes to record the kilometres traveled – and possibly also where they were driven – and then use the information for calculating tax returns.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while one cannot agree on an action in Congress, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how to switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’re only going to use potentially,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, who is planning a record of the miles traveled on all California drivers in the state starting in 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for this is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from the taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is bankrupt.
In America, however, there is no longer as much fuel as before.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 cents per litre) has not increased for 20 years.
At high fuel prices, politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by one cent.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a traffic law expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful alternative in the long term,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is appealing to urban liberals, for example, because the tax could be used to influence driving behaviour in such a way that congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
The California planners rely on the system in developing strategies to achieve the ambitious, legally enshrined goals of the state on climate change.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also inspired by the idea of having drivers pay for the distance covered.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” explains Adrian Moore, Vice President of Policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, had called on Congress to move toward mile-based billing.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the advance and responded to the concerns of MPs from rural areas, representing people who often have to travel many miles on the way to work or the city in everyday life.
Several states and major cities nevertheless move in this direction on their own.
Oregon currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the petroleum tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering such a thing.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently investigating how to implement the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, drivers were skeptical of the idea that the government could track any of their movements.
“Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, Head of Strategy and Result Management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into full-fledged surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data about the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track the miles traveled, but not exactly when and where.
Khan said the public would be more reassuring.
Hunting for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not enter to help states with the taxation of motorists.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance where drivers should pay based on the miles traveled.
But the devices tested by her are also interesting for the road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programs have made major mistakes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they don’t choose a device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average mileage traveled by all residents of the state.
Others hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxable device that can also be used to pay parking fees, to pay insurance only for miles traveled, and to collect real-time speed data from other vehicles, which allows drivers to avoid congestion.
“Car drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits the system offers,” the city’s planning document states.
However, some traffic planners wonder whether the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction maneuver.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by increasing the fuel tax.
An additional one-time fee or annual levy could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
“There is no reason for surgery if an aspirin is sufficient,” said Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s head of legislation and public affairs.
If we do, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
