Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Faraway planets, gravitational waves or black holes – experts from the European Space Agency now have to agree on two major projects they want to launch in the coming years.
30 proposals were available, five are still in the race.
Faraway worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been found by astronomers.
Whether there is life on some of them at least, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should you search for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origins of the cosmos?
Or search for Earth-like planets and perhaps discover extraterrestrial life?
These questions are being asked by those responsible for the European Space Agency Esa.
For their "Cosmic Vision" programme, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that will drive research forward.
The budget for such "L-Missions" is about one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were debated, five of which have now been narrowly chosen.
Numerous committees are examining the proposals, working with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Programme Committee.
In total, ESA has selected four major questions to which the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme, initiated in 2007, should find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
To investigate this question, the Space Telescope "Cheops" is to be launched in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our vicinity will be investigated in more detail.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, the astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres and thus search for "biomarkers": gases that are considered indicators of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately intended to provide information on the prerequisites for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation it emits with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be investigated by way of example.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the Esa has already approved a mission of the M-Class (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is expected to launch in 2017 and monitor the surface and activity of the sun closely.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, Esa is planning the first of the three total L missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
The Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) probe is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is set to investigate the planet's atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europa, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the fundamental physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could show the physicists the way to a new theory under which all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what is it made of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the common matter, which consists of stars, planets, and living beings like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies together, and dark energy, through which the expansion of the universe is accelerated.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", the ESA has already approved an M-Mission here, the launch of which is planned for 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time throughout the sky and thus allow conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves, has the best chance of being approved as an L-Mission.
Physicists understand changes in the structure of spacetime that Albert Einstein predicted nearly 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to date.
Elisa could do that, hope the scientists behind the project.
The mission foresees a detector consisting of two or three probes stationed in space.
Unlike systems on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves created by the Big Bang, providing new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four other proposals still compete for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is to explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which is to detect and investigate Earth-like planets.
Proposals have already been eliminated, among other things, on sample return transport from Mars, on the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, and on solar physics.
