What happens to my email on the way?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
Was e-mail technically implemented in the design of the Internet service similar to conventional mail?
When designing early internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have not taken care to create a stable foundation for a reliable exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
In the first step, Anna’s email program or browser sends the mail to their service provider’s mail server.
For example, if she has a GMail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run via a number of other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are traditional emails being read along the way through the web?
Most emails are read several times by software robots on the go.
The sender’s provider usually checks whether the mail contains a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam email that is deleted immediately or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can show corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people read the emails?
The likelihood of unauthorised people reading an email is extremely low.
Theoretically, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal options to intercept or take note of emails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect emails from reading along?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against co-reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to obscure the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even easy to recognize who has communicated with whom.
