An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should you expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great post-war plan to unify Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Everywhere in the EU, parties gain ground that are EU-hostile or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Euroskeptic Party Alternative for Germany – founded only this year – was able to gain almost five million votes in the Bundestag elections in September, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in conjunction with the forced jacket into which the respective national economy is forced by sticking to the common currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave that.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, Southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage over Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives enacted by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world’s wage fixes do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is on the rise, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, the political elite of France saw the EU as a vehicle that could be used to keep Germany in check and lift Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has pushed Europe down its own economic policy, which is what the troubled French economy is struggling with.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a decisive by-election and thus referred the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour party that it cannot assume a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among the white French of the working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point to which I want to go: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and Southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering with the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of (finally) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which includes saying to Berlin and Brussels what they can put where.
I suspect that Scotland could do quite well in a looser European alliance, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similarly-thinking countries is easier in an unfederated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and keeping our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition had to blame.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to now opt for independence, only to get a austerity policy imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Growing Up Faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not directly mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics in Orlando, Florida this week, paediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz stated that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – usually that’s not a sign that puberty is now fast,” Kaplowitz explained.
Clear indications of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair as well as body odor, are shown in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (the occurrence of the first menstrual period) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When the development of breasts begins, it takes at least two to three years until menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early puberty in girls: The essential guide to dealing with this common problem".
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial, which is actually the beginning of puberty, but it is “early” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a boost in growth before the age of eight years.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
If progress is made faster, tests by an endocronologist may be indicated so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods for delaying early menstruation and repelling another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and the emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reluctant about medication, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and the feelings of girls to be different from their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They are concerned about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her days when she was ten.
Even though there were initial signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home scared and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are causal.
Boys come into puberty similar to girls used to.
Kaplowitz believes that the most persuasive premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study on girls aged six to nine years, which establishes a link between body fat and entering puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, an early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys’ facial and pubic hair grows earlier, the trend towards a full-fledged previous puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than expected.
