“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can help millions of smokers who have tried to quit using all the methods available on the market, but have experienced that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been altered to contain genetic information on the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, causing a smoker not to experience nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal activity levels.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken a “pause,” the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it transforms liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if absolutely certain, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
More likely, however, that smokers would use it to quit.
“Then they know that when they start smoking again, they don’t feel any pleasure about the nicotine vaccine anymore, and that helps them get rid of the habit,” he explains.
