Pawn houses are booming in Singapore as the middle class crisis has arrived
In a pawn shop in Singapore’s Bendemeer shopping centre, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bangle, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay the school fees of her daughters.
“My husband and I just bought a house, there’s all my money in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (approximately 1,730 euros) each month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not sufficient, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it made its exchange, this week became the third pawn shop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
Pledging jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, Singapore’s liens demand an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, which is just over the 15.4 percent demanded by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawn houses offer the advantage that there is no need to verify creditworthiness or proof of income, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
That’s why millions of people in the region turn to lien houses after families feel the pressure from rising cost of living, as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose financial policy in the developed economies, families with lower and middle incomes are looking for pawn houses to make up for the difference in the stuttering economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor’s described growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
According to the agency, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing export weakness and a decrease in consumer demand.
“In the end, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have reinforced the trend to pledge personal items as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city’s 200 pawn houses are gold.
People say to themselves, “The gold price looks good, let’s pledge Grandmother’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
The largest Thai lien operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in customers in its stores in recent months.
The growth in the lien business is so strong that ValueMax, which operates the Bendemeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighbouring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company finances it with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it took this week with its IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders have fallen into the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnhouses not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also do not directly raise the debt.
“Customers borrow items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables does not increase household education,” she explains.
The pawn lending business is increasingly accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use pawns are in financial trouble.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax’s stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, earning up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from every social class come to us.
“This includes wealthy people borrowing for a business or an investment in the short term, or small businesses that need to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
