FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on airplanes (but don’t have cell phone calls)
Passengers can now use their electronic devices from departure to landing to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but not make phone calls on their phones, according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depended on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of the aircraft personnel and the regulations for storing the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the state of the plan, we could very soon approve the extended use of electronic devices,” the FAA said in a statement.
At present, passengers must turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
You may not restart it until the plane has reached a height of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing flight, passengers must turn it off again and must not restart it until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even on take-off, landing and on the rolling field, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been converted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” Glading said.
We are honestly tired of having to feel like guardians on this issue.
Nevertheless, internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers continued to be prohibited, the agency explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still not a “Words With Friends”, the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave a jet of American Airlines publicly because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, must continue to be stowed, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight are also prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices at launch and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national traffic safety expert on CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that air transmission can also disrupt transmission masts," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue last month recommended that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA has increased to ease restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies have mentioned that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore switching off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air passengers in 1966 after reports of disruption of navigation and communication devices by passenger-driven FM radios became known, which at that time represented the latest technology trend.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA in such a way that they don’t care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years when the altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger planes should be suitable for the greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when you scroll around.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the proponents of easing restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to identify problems, but were unable to detect any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the interference with the devices is genuine, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports of pilots speaking for disrupting aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended to the FAA that pilots be allowed to order the passengers to turn off the equipment in case of instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adaptation for travelers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
“We are delighted that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience does not conflict with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
