Scientists were able to shed more light on how a dog’s tail-sweeping relates to its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs swayed more to the right with the tail (from the dog’s point of view), while it was the left side in nervous dogs.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “In humans, it is well known that the left and right brain halves respond differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right brain half is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail-sweeping of their fellow species, the researchers monitored the animals as these films looked at other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the tail moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the waving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tendency of the tail was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog waving), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience what movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and the swinging with the tail in one direction is more linked to friendly behavior and the right side produces less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their animal’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert in dog behavior and a visiting fellow at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the University of Bristol, explained that this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it is a satisfied dog.
Another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada said: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when his ‘tail’ is rolling to the left rather than to the right rather than getting restless – just the other way around than in the Italian study.”
According to him, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain halves are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” said Bradshaw.
However, since their behavior can be easily recorded, it will probably not take long for us to understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
