I have elected President Obama twice in hopes that change is possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by Republican blockade tactics
The blockade policy does not apologise for Obamacare’s website problems, the drone attacks
Obama’s 2008 election campaign memoirs are a sad reminder of what would have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a very sad book.
It’s a book that I thought would cheer me up and give me hope again during the turbulent second year of my medical studies.
It’s called “The Audacity to Win” and depicts Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential election memoirs.
When I finish my patient records in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and took a speech away.
The election became a landslide victory and news spokesmen stopped to point out the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates wept with joy and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had 82% approval.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a bad awakening, as if torn from a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first gave my vote, something has actually changed.
But it's just not something I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and versatile things Obama has accomplished, from the adoption of the Affordable Care Act on health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of forced seclusion of homosexuality in the army, and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that the blockade tactic of party politics has tilted too many aspirations to bring our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times to colleagues and acquaintances, I’ve come to the end with my attempts at explanation.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican blockade policy cannot explain why it is allowed to listen to foreign heads of state or to kill innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data about Americans’ private lives and why whistleblowers are being punished who disclose state misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits are circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the results of a report stating that the White House’s efforts to pacify the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon government.”
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at the age of 18 that government work could be contrary to the previous political campaigns.
Obviously, the MP’s office is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape the public discussion.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and unfermented alternative, he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressures of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard of for so long.
But with Obama’s approval levels falling to below 45% this week, the return to 2008 has become all the harder due to this book.
It awakens within me the longing for the many promises that have dissolved in air.
This week I read a section in the book that describes how Obama had to put in a heavy loss against Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with the election helpers after the decision, he told his employees to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
“I want us to find our magic again,” he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree more strongly with you.
