RBS suspends two foreign exchange traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange department, including two people familiar with the situation; this is another indication that the global government investigation into the alleged manipulation of the currency market is rapidly taking off.
Some of the world’s largest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank, and RBS, confirmed that they are working with authorities to investigate the world’s largest financial market, where $5.3 trillion a day will change ownership.
The two traders would be the first RBS employees to be suspended in the expanding investigation that entails the scandal surrounding the Libor interbank business.
The bank, which did not comment on the suspensions, confirmed this month that it had received information requests from authorities.
“Our investigation on this issue continues and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and other regulators,” the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, people close to the situation indicated that the RBS had forwarded the records of emails and instant messages sent to and from a former merchant to the UK supervisory authority, the Financial Conduct Authority.
This trader, Richard Usher, had left RBS in 2010 and is now said to have been expelled from his current position as European leader of Forex spot trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot trading at Citi, was suspended this week, and Matt Gardiner, former chief currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended at Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders were accused of any misconduct.
Usher’s instant message group included bankers at Barclays and Citigroup, people close to the situation said.
UBS announced this week that it had taken steps against some of its employees after the Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating a suspected manipulation of the foreign exchange market at a number of Swiss banks.
At least six authorities around the world – the European Commission, Finma, the Swiss competition authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are currently dealing with allegations that bankers are supposed to have agreed on transactions on the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also initiated internal investigations or received information requests from authorities, people familiar with the situation said.
Banks comb through instant messages and e-mails from several years in search of cases of misconduct.
The news of these investigations has upset traders in an area that has been one of the most profitable of investment banks’ trading units in recent years, but has been under pressure this year because low volatility in currencies limits the chances for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the affair, saying it is almost impossible to manipulate the extensive and highly liquid foreign exchange market, but leading traders believe this is not necessarily true.
A leading trader noted that despite the enormous daily volume in forex trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between the various trading platforms and the increasing use of banks' own internal platforms leads to "the ability to influence the market even with very low ticket prices".
The news came out the same day when Credit Suisse announced that it had terminated a trader at its London Exchange Traded Funds office this week after causing a loss of nearly $6 million at the end of last year.
The Bank promptly informed the competent authorities and cooperated with them.
“We are sure that the dealer has acted alone and that the matter is contained,” said Credit Suisse.
