Supreme Court confirms Obama's health law
It’s a big victory for the Obama administration: The U.S. Supreme Court today ruled that the health law closely linked to Barack Obama is constitutional.
With five to four votes, the judges ruled that the single mandate of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act – forcing U.S. citizens to take out health insurance or pay a penalty by 2014 – is constitutional under the state’s tax authority.
Supreme Judge John Roberts sided with the four more liberal members of the Chamber, while Judges Scalia, Thomas, Alito and Kennedy opted against it.
The court also confirmed the remaining sections of the 2,700-page law, and also held that the health law stipulates that states should either extend the access requirements for Medicaid or otherwise remove all state Medicaid funding is not unconstitutional.
The lawsuit was filed by 26 states and the National Federation of Independent Business.
The law had been resolutely rejected by all leading Republican presidential candidates, including the ultimate challenger Mitt Romney, in the 2012 pre-election campaign.
