Egypt pledges first freely elected president
Mohammed Mursi takes office, but his day of triumph may not mean the end of political disputes in Egypt.
Islamist Mohammed Mursi promised a “new Egypt” when he was sworn in as the first freely elected president of the country, succeeding Husni Mubarak, who had been expelled from office 16 months earlier.
With his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Mursi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and Egypt’s fifth head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy about 60 years ago.
He took the oath in front of the 18 judges of the court, dressed in black robes, which has its seat on the Nile and is modelled on an ancient Egyptian temple.
“We are striving for a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic,” Mursi said at the ceremony, which was broadcast live on state television.
“Today, the Egyptian people have laid the foundations for a new life – absolute freedom, genuine democracy and stability,” said 60-year-old Morsi, an engineer trained in the US and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that had been targeted by the respective government since its founding 84 years ago as a banned organization.
Hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building when Mursi arrived in a small car convoy shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters had gathered before the court to cheer on the new president, and unlike the presidential splendor of the Mubarak era, traffic was only briefly stopped so that the car convoy could cross the usually busy road that connects the city center with the southern suburbs.
Spotted as an uncharismatic “replacement wheel” of the Brotherhood, his personal prestige has increased since his victory and a Friday speech, in which he presented himself not only as a candidate of the Islamists, but of all those who wanted to achieve the aspirations of the 2011 uprising against the authoritarian Mubarak.
“Egypt today is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,” Morsi, dressed in a blue suit with a red tie, told the judges in the wood-paneled chamber where he took office.
Later, Mursi went to the University of Cairo, where he was to give his inaugural speech.
He was officially greeted by an army chapel playing the national anthem he listened to in a habacht position.
The military leader, Field Marshal Hussein Tantawi, was present.
Upon his arrival, he was greeted by hundreds of attendees in the university's largest lecture hall with speech choirs of "The Army and the People are a Hand".
Established in 1908 as a bastion of secular education, the University of Cairo developed into a stronghold of Islamist student groups in the 1970s.
On Friday, Mursi took a symbolic oath in Tahir Square, the birthplace of the uprising that led to the end of Mubarak’s authoritarian rule last year, and vowed to reclaim presidential powers taken over by the military council from the head of state who had been chased out of office.
But with the official oath being taken before the court and not as usual before Parliament, he bows to the will of the military, which indicates that the power struggle will continue.
Mursi’s speech in Tahir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
