On the way through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle Brings Free Medical Assistance to Remote Villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in the West African country, only one for 5,000 people.
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose him as the “CNN Hero of the Year”.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation formed that spread to his brain and caused a hematoma there that would affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle comments.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, in the United States, the relationship is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health expenditure in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
Poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer in Bwelle ripened the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team conducted 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Nearly every Friday, he and up to 30 people force themselves into minibuses and drive the tightened medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain into the villages that need help.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
More than once, they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are received like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation that the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and Bwelle – with his wide smile and his limitless energy – is happy to attend the cheerful celebration.
The next morning, the team will start examining hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per trip,” says Bwelle.
You come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
Surgery usually takes place in a school, town hall, or apartment; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for their neighbor.
The lighting for the operating room and the disinfection equipment is supplied by the generator of the group and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning on Sunday.
It’s a strenuous chorus, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They’re drumming all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team drives back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that their work makes a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free surgery of a groin fracture he received now allows him to work again.
“This is changing my family’s future,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his charitable activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s going to sleep,” says Katie O’Malley, who studies medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and volunteers in Bwelle’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain hands-on experience that they would never get at home.
“We can be involved in operations where we help pat blood or keep the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies with them.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes care of the accommodation, transport and guidance.
“He’s without a doubt a hero,” says O’Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise that he has given to his Father brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this work,” says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I do it to make people laugh again and to alleviate the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and learn how you can help.
