Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters long, a sewage canal from Roman times is preserved below Cologne.
If you visit Cologne, you will not pass the cathedral.
Around 157 meters, the two towers rise to the sky and make it the second-highest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors who admire the two filigree church towers suspect that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the Cologne underworld.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts very unspectacular: "We start in the underground car park," Schulze says.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore, from the remains of the old city walls, only that which was not too large stood still.
Most of the users of the car park now also rush past the Roman remains and only park their car.
But if you look more closely, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal bars in the D2 parking deck.
You can see about five meters high ruins made of hand-plate-sized stones.
"These are remnants of the Roman city wall built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze says.
Before returning to daylight, Schulze lets the participants take a look in a dark, 15-metre-deep shaft on the upper level of the park.
This is the fountain of the old dome, which unfortunately is hardly noticed.
The next stop of the tour is the Prätorium, and here the participants descend again into the depths.
Here we experience the office of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the pretor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which means in good German as much as "City of Roman law and city of Agrippa, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the praetorium is the former governor's palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the entrance hall of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here at around 120 meters in length.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze encourages the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After getting the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walkable shaft.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater, which was indispensable for the ritual washings.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is due to begin shortly.
However, there will be a few more years until completion.
