In an unprecedented admission, John Kerry declares that US spying has gone “inappropriately too far”
John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, hinted at a softening of the US’s defensive stance on its surveillance programs, saying that espionage had gone “inappropriately too far” in certain cases.
The Secretary of State also admitted that he and Barack Obama were responsible for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities became public.
Through the leaked information, the U.S. government has fallen into a diplomatic storm of indignation on the part of its allies.
Speaking at the Open Government conference in London, Kerry said: “Without a doubt, the President and I, as well as others in the government, have learned of some things that have happened almost by autopilot, simply because the ability to do so was what goes back to the Second World War and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, to September 11.
He subsequently became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, "In some cases, this has gone inappropriately too far."
The President is determined to create clarity and therefore conducts a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons will not be impaired in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force of good and many lives had been saved through its surveillance operations.
He added: “We are dealing with a new world where people are willing to blow themselves up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is obsessed with killing people, blowing up the air and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop this before it happens?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people because we have learned of such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. legislators will travel to Europe to dispel concerns about alleged U.S. espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue to work with the U.S. in anti-terror efforts, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he had spoken to representatives of the European Parliament and other individuals this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terror organizations due to the frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
"It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans stay on board in view of our joint efforts against terrorism," Murphy, who is a Democrat for the first time in the Senate and chairs the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
In addition, I am going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, regardless of their anger over the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has collected millions of phone data in Europe have strained relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the intelligence service said this week that the reports were inaccurate and were based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations cited documents passed on by Snowden, according to which the NSA had monitored the mobile phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of national intelligence, James Clapper, defended espionage among allies as necessary and declared that this was common on both sides.
In all the turmoil, Murphy said his agency was preparing the congressional trip to take place this year, hoping the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other participating Members will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact itinerary is still being worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relationships, he also said that there would be some “serious words.”
He said European governments should be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programs they themselves have been using for years.
"While we can change our surveillance programmes and thus better protect Europeans' rights, they must also agree with the fact that we are not the only ones who are spying," Murphy said.
